<div id="review_3232624441" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3232624441" />
    <a title="Riju Ganguly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2736147-riju-ganguly"><img alt="Riju Ganguly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1524633338p2/2736147.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3232624441?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Riju Ganguly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Riju Ganguly" href="/user/show/2736147-riju-ganguly">Riju Ganguly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3232624441" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10516352320210666713">Edogawa Rampo (whose actual name was Hirai Taro) had written these longish stories long-long ago, amidst settings that are supposedly too far away from post-modern readers like us. But such is the brilliance of the stories, perfectly captured and translated into English by James B. Harris, that they appear absolutely modern.<br/>How did that happen?<br/>It happened because like the very best of writers Rampo had built his tales using one ingredient that never, NEVER changes: the human psyche!<br/>This book con</span>
  <span id="freeText10516352320210666713" style="display:none">Edogawa Rampo (whose actual name was Hirai Taro) had written these longish stories long-long ago, amidst settings that are supposedly too far away from post-modern readers like us. But such is the brilliance of the stories, perfectly captured and translated into English by James B. Harris, that they appear absolutely modern.<br />How did that happen?<br />It happened because like the very best of writers Rampo had built his tales using one ingredient that never, NEVER changes: the human psyche!<br />This book contains nine stories. Many of them have been scavenged or plagiarised by lots and lots of authors. Nevertheless, the originals outshine all those imitations by virtue of their muted presence and delicate imageries.<br />The stories are:<br />1. The Human Chair<br />2. The Psychological Test<br />3. The Caterpillar<br />4. The Cliff<br />5. The Hell of Mirrors<br />6. The Twins<br />7. The Red Chamber<br />8. Two Crippled Men<br />9. The Traveler with the Pasted Rag Picture<br />Some of these stories involve crime. Several more have themes of punishment therein. Madness and macabre raise their head in a few stories.<br />But every one of them are stunning in terms of their abilities in the depiction of the mystery of human mind!<br />If you are an admirer of psychological thrillers or mysteries, then this one is essential read for you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10516352320210666713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


