    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_828275128" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/828275128" />
    <a title="Ronald" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2443909-ronald"><img alt="Ronald" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1411263222p2/2443909.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/828275128?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ronald" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ronald" href="/user/show/2443909-ronald">Ronald</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer828275128" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13582417670180887019">Edogawa Rampo was a Japanese writer of mystery and other genre fiction. His literary hero was Edgar Allan Poe, and that was a major reason for me in getting this book for my Kindle.<br/><br/>Most of the stories in this book are &apos;naturalistic&apos;. For me, a naturalistic story of horror or suspense, in order to be effective, has to have an unpredictable plot.<br/><br/>Thus these stories with a unpredictable plot I found excellent:<br/><br/>&quot;The Human Chair&quot; A woman who is a popular writer of mysteries receives a disturbing letter</span>
  <span id="freeText13582417670180887019" style="display:none">Edogawa Rampo was a Japanese writer of mystery and other genre fiction. His literary hero was Edgar Allan Poe, and that was a major reason for me in getting this book for my Kindle.<br /><br />Most of the stories in this book are 'naturalistic'. For me, a naturalistic story of horror or suspense, in order to be effective, has to have an unpredictable plot.<br /><br />Thus these stories with a unpredictable plot I found excellent:<br /><br />"The Human Chair" A woman who is a popular writer of mysteries receives a disturbing letter in the mail from a man who constructed a chair big enough for him to hide in. The story has an unexpected ending.<br /><br />"The Cliff" A woman discusses the failed plot by her previous husband to kill her, and also foils a plot to kill her by her current husband. But is what she says really the case? The story has a wickedly twist ending.<br /><br />"The Twins" A man kills his twin brother, and takes up the role of his dead brother (for example, living with his dead brother's wife). Under this guise, this man commits crimes and avoids detection...for a while.<br /><br />"The Red Chamber" A man tells a story to a secret society about the murders he has committed. His method of operation is by indirect means, by making the death look like an accident. The story has a twist ending.<br /><br />"Two Crippled Man" A man tells about the crimes he has committed while sleepwalking. But at the end he is given another explanation for the crimes.<br /><br />Other stuff not quite as good:<br /><br />"The Psychological Test" is a whodunit story. The murderer is really caught, when, undergoing a second round of questioning, is caught in a contradiction. I'm not a big fan of the whodunit story, but fans of the genre might like this story.<br /><br />"The Caterpillar" is about the relationship between a woman, and her husband, who, because of war, had all four limbs amputated, cannot hear, and his face is disfigured. This story could be classed as horror. The plot is straightforward.<br /><br />"The Hell of Mirrors" The narrator's story is about his friend's mad obsession with mirrors and other optical instruments. No speculative element in this story, and no plot twists. I even doubt that the object that the friend created at the end of the story can cause madness.<br /><br />"The Traveler With The Pasted Rag Picture" Speculative fiction, and a train story to boot. This is a bittersweet fantasy about a man who caught a glimpse of a beautiful woman, and his obsession with finding her. <br /><br /><br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="13582417670180887019" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


